Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. miscConds.notes:

result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Danielle Mary Elworthy

records.addlTxt: 01:38 PM Defendant Danielle Mary Elworthy appeared by zoom technology by video means along with Attorney William A. Schembera by phone means. Attorney Jon D. Seifert appeared by phone means for Plaintiff State of Wisconsin.  We have an agreement.  DAGPA for 1 year at the end of the agreement, count 1 shall be amended to County Ordinance with costs of $330.50.  Court advises of right to PH.  Ms. Elworthy waives her right to PH.  Court finds waiver of PH done knowingly, voluntarily & intelligently.  Court advises of charge of posess a controlled substance THC as 2nd offense/max. penalties.  State will dismiss count 2.  Court advises of constitutional rights waiving to plea to the charge.  Defendant admits she had a prior offense.  To the charge of possessing THC 2nd offense defendant pleads guilty.  Subject to the deferred acceptance contract, defer acceptance for 1 year and dismiss count 2.  Court corrects it's comment the matter will not be dismissed but amended to an ordinance violation with a penalty.  Ms. Elworthy agrees with the agreement.  Court will sign the contract.
Proposed Order for Deferred Acceptance of Guilty or No Contest Plea Agreement
Waiver of Rights to Personal Appearance
Adjourned initial appearance on March 1, 2022 at 01:30 pm.
